{
  "version": 5,
  "_comment": "Bootstrap fleet policies (Keel M2, extended for M5 wave-1, wave-2 AND wave-3 connectors). Installed to ~/.assistant/policies/policies.json on first triage run when no live file exists. On later runs a version bump here ADDs any rule ids missing from the installed file (never overwrites or removes user rules) and ledgers the upgrade. Ordered, first-match-wins. Every id has a fixture in evals/policy/<id>/ enforced by tests/test_policy.py coverage. M5 wave-1: github + gmail rules (kinds are the notification reason / mechanical newsletter|direct|message). M5 wave-2: gcal + slack rules are now present because their producers (bin/connectors/gcal.py, slack-events.py) exist and their WorldEvent kinds are known and mechanical (gcal kind=event_upcoming with refs.window horizon; slack kind = app_mention|dm|message from Slack's own event metadata) — the M2-era data-hiding hazard (guessing a schema before the producer existed) no longer applies. M5 wave-3: outlook rules — the producer (bin/connectors/outlook.py) exists and its WorldEvent kind is mechanical from Microsoft Graph metadata (direct|cc|newsletter|message, DIRECT-ADDRESSED classified before any newsletter signal per SEC2 so a direct message is never auto-dropped). No rule uses the `auto` lane (the triage lane map structurally cannot emit auto; auto is confirmed-policy-only). Mutations to the LIVE file go through confirmed `policy` proposals, not hand edits.",
